\strong{Part Two}

Now, you\'re ready to choose a directory to delete.

The total disk space available to the filesystem is \emph{\code{70000000}}. To run
the update, you need unused space of at least \emph{\code{30000000}}. You need to
find a directory you can delete that will \emph{free up enough space} to run
the update.

In the example above, the total size of the outermost directory (and
thus the total amount of used space) is \code{48381165}; this means that the
size of the \emph{unused} space must currently be \code{21618835}, which isn\'t
quite the \code{30000000} required by the update. Therefore, the update still
requires a directory with total size of at least \code{8381165} to be deleted
before it can run.

To achieve this, you have the following options:
\itemize{
\item Delete directory \code{e}, which would increase unused space by \code{584}.
\item Delete directory \code{a}, which would increase unused space by \code{94853}.
\item Delete directory \code{d}, which would increase unused space by
\code{24933642}.
\item Delete directory \code{/}, which would increase unused space by
\code{48381165}.
}

Directories \code{e} and \code{a} are both too small; deleting them would not free
up enough space. However, directories \code{d} and \code{/} are both big enough!
Between these, choose the \emph{smallest}: \code{d}, increasing unused space by
\emph{\code{24933642}}.

Find the smallest directory that, if deleted, would free up enough space
on the filesystem to run the update. \emph{What is the total size of that
directory?}
